Patient Note: A 30-year-old generally healthy woman presents with shortness of breath that had started 2 hours before admission. She has had no health problems in the past besides 2 natural abortions. She had given birth to a healthy child 3 weeks before. On examination, she is apprehensive, tachypneic and tachycardic, her blood pressure is 110/70 and her oxygen saturation 92%. Otherwise, physical examination is unremarkable. Her chest x-ray and CBC are normal.

Inclusion Criteria: Inclusion Criteria:
Healthy pregnant females > 18 years of age with singleton pregnancies (either nulliparous or multiparous);
less than 17 weeks gestation;
a pre pregnancy BMI < 40 kg/m2 (owing to the fact that severe obesity with BMI> 40 may have limitations with respect to physical activity);
plans to deliver at a Hamilton or London regional hospital or by home birth and willing to attend research visits at the community site where they were recruited;
able to tolerate dairy foods;
approval of primary care provider;
able to provide signed informed consent.

Assessment of Eligibility: This patient is currently pregnant and under 18 weeks gestation. She has had only two natural abortions and recently gave birth to a healthy child. Her chest x-ray and CBC have produced normal results, and on examination she is apprehensive, tachypneic and tachycardic, her blood pressure is 110/70 and oxygen saturation 92%. Her body mass index (BMI) is not over 40 kg/m2.

The BHIP clinical trial is focused on helping women achieve healthier pregnancies through a structured high dairy protein diet and walking program, or usual prenatal care by their care provider. This patient is currently in the first half of her pregnancy, and based on the information provided her BMI is also within the acceptable range.

In summary, the patient seems likely to benefit from the BHIP program, and we can safely say: Trial-level eligibility: 2) Highly likely to refer this patient for this clinical trial.</s>
